  "doc_id": "41847",
  "text": "Self-administration of the opiate agonists has been studied as another way to assess their reward properties. Animals quickly learn to respond to receive injections of opiates, including morphine [CITATION_1] and, especially, heroin [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . The self-administration rates of morphine were positively correlated with previous exposure to morphine [CITATION_5] , suggesting the development of tolerance. With a progressive ratio schedule of self-administration of heroin, designed to restrict intake and minimize dependence, final rates of responding were stable and did not increase with chronic reinforcement, so that such a schedule was effective in preventing dependence. Naltrexone reduced the final rate of responding, suggesting that the antagonist attenuated the reinforcement received from heroin [CITATION_6] . Responding, however, was increased with 3-funaltrexamine, naloxonazine, and naltrindole, but not with nor-binaltorphimine in more typical methods of self-administration [CITATION_7] , indicating that the schedule of reinforcement was crucial to the results. In addition, the study demonstrated that the u receptors are most involved in selfadministration, then the #~ subtype and b receptors, and that the K receptors are not involved [CITATION_8] . Lesions of the pedunculopontine nucleus, which is thought to mediate opiate reward, reduced self-administration of heroin, indicating that heroin must not be rewarding after the lesions and providing support for the importance of the nucleus in the reinforcing properties of opiates [CITATION_9] ,",
